node.text:
—Long overdue for not only another ASB Filmz production but really a collaboration with some of our closest pals that are fellow locals and neighbors in Seaside, California. We're talking about @otherbrotherbeer! These folks opened last October, after years of planning and community outreach. Their presence is critical in the progression of our local beer culture, and they've been releasing some incredible suds! For this collaboration we focused on creating a fermentation profile that was neutral, highlighting fresh Nelson Sauvin, Galaxy & New Zealand Cascade (also called Taiheke) from the 2020 crop year. One whiff & sip will not leave you guessing the hop profile in this one, it's definitively Southern Hemisphere all the way: ripe mango, passion fruit, guava and lil' bit of the diesel dank! Don't sleep on this beer, plenty of 4-packs await on burphopsnow.com for shipping, and we've got a bunch at all three locations. Even grab a pint on draft outside at @heermannslanding at Other Brother Beer!
...
As for the video production, we should state that it has absolutely nothing to do with the pun on the iconic 1987 film upon which the beer is based on. Just some good old fashioned competitive goofiness, reflecting what an actual collaboration at our brewery is still like, Covid or not!!

WAVE JAMMER (this was our first motion picture production, circa 2017)🤙🍻
....

node.text: The crew at @yakimachief came down just before shit hit the fan to highlight our crew and shine the light on Double Cone, our 2019 Alpha King Champion beer!! node.text:
HOT PINK SHERBURPS!!! 
...
Could this be our favorite Sherburps yet?! Quite possibly. Pink grapefruit, pink guava, red dragonfruit, and pomegranate has made for a delectable combo in our opinion. You gotta try this latest imperial sour of ours, it's pretty insane. Available now on asb.beer for shipping in California, and at all three locations in the Monterey Bay this weekend! 😎🤘🏻🍻

To our beloved Salinas Taproom patrons...it's time we give an update on where we're at with the reopening our Dayton St. location:
...
Earlier this year, we were hopeful that our Salinas Taproom would reopen sometime by mid Summer. The two major hurdles we are still facing is the lack of additional warehouse space, and an uncertain supply chain. During the pandemic we had no choice but to use the taproom space not only as a staging area for our online beer sales, but also to store raw materials that we've had to purchase in bulk. Sourcing these items has been anything but easy, and we've faced challenging inventory levels due to crazy long lead times and lack of availability. We had two prospects for additional warehouse space that we started inquiring about last February, one of which was supposed to come to fruition in June. It looks like both of those have now been pushed back indefinitely, and it's made us realize some hard truths. It hurts us to say this, but reopening will be a very difficult path. Especially as we consider the additional beer we'll have to brew to support two new locations next year - Alvarado on Main in Old Town Salinas, and the Alvarado Beer Garden with the Monterey Bay F.C. at CSUMB. Where many have once sat and enjoyed a pint, we will eventually need to house additional tanks in that space. Not saying never again, just not anytime soon. We would eventually like to hold events at our Dayton St. location, and one day offer brewery tours. But for right now and the immediate future, we are focusing on getting through the lasting effects of the pandemic. (continued in comments below)

Have you tried CNJ lately?!?!🍊🤤🍊
…
We took the feedback we received from the 7th Anniversary Edition, and incorporated much of this into our production process going forward. We feel it certainly helps our flagship Hazy DIPA stand out in a crowd. 🍊⚡️☀️
…
The big changes mostly come in the form of yeast & enzymes; we’ve worked out the kinks of a new strain that squeezes out more tropical hop flavors through biotransformation, increasing the concentration of compounds responsible for the juice-like flavors without adding any actual fruit. Since our hops are constantly changing along with the growing season, every hop lot we get is unique to the crop year and variability is the one constant. As a result, we’re developing new dry hop blends for CNJ fairly often. Currently, we’re loving a blend of two Nelson Sauvin lots, and a combination of Mosaic & Citra (T90 and Cryo Lupulin powder), and a touch of super oily / dank New Zealand grown Waimea. We find this blend, at a rate of over 8 lbs per barrel, is highly complementary to the increased levels of thiols and monoterpenes produced during fermentation.

...

It's crazy, crazy drinkable; dry, bitter and chock full of tropical oily hop flavor & aroma. A very special beer to us, brewed only a few times a year.
